td.span: decibel

The decibel (dB) is a unit of sound intensity. One bel represents the logarithm of a ratio between two power quantities of 10:1, or the logarithm of a ratio between two field quantities of √10:1. One decibel is one tenth (deci-) of one bel.
manmonth
The manmonth is a unit of count defining the number of months for a person or persons to perform an undertaking.
byte
The byte is a unit of information equal to 8 bits.
ampere
The ampere (A) is the base unit of electric current in the International System of Units, equivalent to 6.24×1018 elementary charges, such as electrons, moving through a surface in one second.
bar

The bar (bar) is a non-SI unit of pressure (i.e. outside of the International System of Units), defined as exactly equal to 100 000 Pa, 10⁵ Pa, which is slightly less than the current average atmospheric pressure on Earth at sea level.
bit

The bit (b), short for "binary digit", is a non-SI unit of information (i.e. outside of the International System of Units) used in computing and digital communications, defined as the minimum amount of information required to make one simple yes-or-no decision at the lowest level in a system.
becquerel

The becquerel (Bq) is a derived unit of radioactivity in the International System of Units, defined as the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second, 1 Bq = s⁻¹.
mole

The mole (mol) is the base unit for amount of substance in the International System of Units, defined as the amount of a chemical substance that contains exactly 6.02214076 × 1023 constitutive particles, e.g. atoms, molecules, ions or electrons.
nanometre
The nanometre (nm) is a unit of length in the International System of Units, equal to one billionth of a metre, 10⁻⁹ m (0.000000001 m).
candela

The candela (cd) is the base unit of luminous intensity in the International System of Units. It is defined as the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540×1012 hertz and has a radiant intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian.
degree Celsius

The degree Celsius (°C) is a unit of temperature used by the International System of Units. The scale used to be based on 0 °C for the freezing point of water and 100 °C for the boiling point of water. The degree Celsius and the Celsius scale are now defined by absolute zero and the triple point of Vienna Standard Mean Ocean Water.
square centimetre
The square centimetre (cm²) is a unit of area in the International System of Units, equivalent to the area formed by a square measuring 1 cm by 1 cm, 10⁻⁴ m².
cubic centimetre
The cubic centimetre (cm³) is a unit of volume in the International System of Units, equivalent to the volume formed by a cube measuring 1 cm by 1 cm by 1 cm, 10⁻⁶ m³.
centimetre
The centimetre (cm) is a unit of length in the International System of Units, equivalent to one hundredth of a metre, 10⁻² m (0.01 m).
terajoule
The terajoule (TJ) is a derived unit of energy in the International System of Units, equivalent to one trillion, 1000 000 000 000 (10¹²), joules.
gigabyte
The gigabyte is a unit of information equal to 10⁹ bytes.
gram
The gram (g) is a unit of mass in the International System of Units (SI), equivalent to one thousandth of the SI base unit, the kilogram, 10⁻³ kg (0.001 kg).
gross tonnage
The gross tonnage (GT) is a nonlinear unit of measurement, equivalent to the volume of all of a ship's enclosed spaces (from keel to funnel) measured to the outside of the hull framing.
gigawatt-hour
The gigawatt-hour (GWh, GW⋅h) is a composite unit of energy in the International System of Units, equivalent to a million (10⁶) kilowatt-hours.
hectare
The hectare (ha) is a unit of area in the International System of Units, equivalent to 10 000 square meters, 10⁴ m².
hectolitre
The hectolitre (hl) is a unit of fluid volume (or capacity), equivalent to the volume of hundred litres, 100 l, or 10⁻¹ m³ (0.1 m³).
hertz
The hertz (Hz) is the derived unit of frequency in the International System of Units, defined as one cycle per second.
hour
The hour (h) is a unit of time accepted for use with the International System of Units, equivalent to 1⁄24 of a day, 3600 seconds (scientifically reckoned as 3599–3601 seconds).
joule

The joule (J) is a derived unit of energy in the International System of Units, equivalent to the energy transferred to (or work done on) an object when a force of one newton acts on that object in the direction of its motion through a distance of one metre.
kelvin

The Kelvin (K) is the base unit of temperature in the International System of Units. The Kelvin scale is an absolute thermodynamic temperature scale using as its null point absolute zero, the temperature at which all thermal motion ceases.
kilogram
The kilogram (kg) is the base unit of mass in the International System of Units. It remains defined by a platinum alloy cylinder, the international prototype kilogram stored in Saint-Cloud, Paris.
kilometre per hour
The kilometre per hour (km/h) is a unit of speed in the International System of Units, equivalent to the number of kilometres covered in one hour.
square kilometre
The square kilometre (km²) is a unit of area in the International System of Units, equivalent to the area formed by a square measuring 1 km by 1 km, 10⁶ m².
kilometre
The kilometre (km) is a unit of length in the International System of Units, equivalent to 1000 meters, 10³ m, or about 0.621 miles.
kilowatt-hour
The kilowatt-hour (kWh, kW⋅h) is a composite unit of energy in the International System of Units, equivalent to the energy provided by a thousand watts in one hour.
kilowatt
The kilowatt (kW) is a unit of power in the International System of Units, equivalent to one thousand watts, 10³ W.
labour hour
The labour hour is a unit of time defining the number of labour hours.
litre

The litre (l) is a unit of volume accepted for use with the International System of Units, representing the volume of 10 cm × 10 cm × 10 cm, 1000 cubic centimetres (cm³) and is thus equal to one thousandth of a cubic metre, 10⁻³ m³, or 1 cubic decimetre (dm³).
megawatt
The megawatt (MW) is a unit of power in the International System of Units, equivalent to million watts, 10⁶ W.
milligram
The milligram (mg) is a unit of mass in the International System of Units, equivalent to one thousandth of a gramme, 10⁻³ g (0.001 g), or 10⁻⁶ kg (0.000001 kg).
minute
The minute (min) is a unit of time accepted for use with the International System of Units, equivalent to 1⁄60 of an hour, or 60 seconds.
millilitre

The millilitre (ml) is a unit of fluid volume (or capacity), equivalent to one thousandth of a litre (0.001 l), 10⁻⁶ m³. The millilitre is not a unit in the International System of Units (SI), but is accepted for use with SI units and prefixes by the International Committee for Weights and Measures.
millimetre
The millimetre (mm) is a unit of length in the International System of Units, equivalent to one thousandth of a metre, 10⁻³ m (0.001 m).
square metre
The square metre (m²) is a unit of area in the International System of Units, equivalent to the area formed by a square measuring 1 m by 1 m, 1 m².
metre

The metre (m) is the base unit of length in some metric systems, including the International System of Units. The metre is defined as the length of the path travelled by light in a vacuum in 1/299 792 458 second.
metre per second
The metre per second (m/s) is a unit of speed in the International System of Units, equivalent to the number of metres covered in one second.
newton

The newton (N) is a derived unit of force in the International System of Units, representing the force needed to accelerate one kilogram of mass at the rate of one metre per second squared in the direction of the applied force, (kg × m)/s².
pascal
The pascal (Pa) is a derived unit of pressure in the International System of Units, defined as one newton per square metre, 1 N/m².
second

The second (s) is the base unit of time in the International System of Units (SI), commonly understood and historically defined as 1⁄86400 of a day. However, it is defined by the SI as the duration of 9 192 631 770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the caesium-133 atom.
tonne-kilometre
The tonne-kilometre (tkm) is a unit of measurement used for calculating the quantity of traffic, representing the transport of one tonne of goods over a distance of one kilometre.
tonne

The (metric) tonne (t) is a non-SI unit of mass (i.e. outside of the International System of Units), equivalent to one thousand kilograms, 10³ kg (1000 kg), or approximately the mass of one cubic meter of water at four degrees Celsius. It is accepted for use with SI units and prefixes by the International Committee for Weights and Measures.
tonne of oil equivalent
The tonne of oil equivalent (toe) is a unit of energy, defined as the amount of energy released by burning one tonne of crude oil. It is approximately 42 gigajoules.
volt

The volt (V) is the derived unit for electric potential, electric potential difference (voltage) and electromotive force, defined as the difference in electric potential between two points of a conducting wire when an electric current of one ampere dissipates one watt of power between those points.
watt
The watt (W) is a unit of power in the International System of Units, defined as a derived unit of one joule per second and used to quantify the rate of energy transfer.
